<font color="#FF0000">I FEEL WORTHLESS AND DIRTY! </font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov 16 10:47:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
MTF.  <br>
Great job, <br><br>
&quot;I could never refuse a medivac..regardless of the weather or enemy situation..not because I was heroic but because I was indebted...and was humbled by the unrecorded heroism of many low ranking infantrymen who faced death for me and my country.&quot; I love you bro,<br><br>
Talk about feeling helpless, the medivac chopper was coming in to pick up our wounded on Novemeber 26th,1967. We had assaulted across an open field earlier that day. Miraculously we had made it across without taking a casulity. But, then we were stopped by a well-entrenched and heavily reinforced NVA battalion. Six hours later, the first medivac is attempting to come in.<br><br>
 <br>
I had already melted one gun barrel, 12-18 dead Marines are laid out about 100 feet away to my left, they were from our company, Mike Company and some from Lima. A string of other Marines are pinned down, by a sniper and heavy gunfire at the bottom of the small hill. They are clutched behind small graves, bushes and flooded rice paddies, not much cover for them. The sniper has moved in closer to us, We can hear his log barrel rifle taking well aimed shots at the CP.<br><br>
Our Lieutenant, one brave, honorable men that we would follow anywhere calls out to us to open up, to provide cover for the medivac chopper to land. <br><br>
The barrel I had stuck in the gun, has been malfuncting, the bag we had carried it in, had a hole in it and it got full of mud and grime. No, cleaning gear, no oil we had used it all up, and had lost the rest. This was now our six-day of the on again, off again contact. We had already lost about 100 men, 42 from our platoon alone, some of them had been brand new reinforcement whom I never met. <br><br>
I opened up, as does the rest of the platoon.  20-30 rounds later, the gun malfunctions, I tear it apart to clean it out, the chopper is coming in. Mattie mattles cease firing after only a couple a rounds a piece, only the two M-14 in our platoon are firing, I could hear the Lt.’s .45 going off, I’m trying to clean the gun, with what ever I can, mud and grime all over the place, bullets striking just in front of me. <br><br>
Welsh, jumps in, next to me. He’s out of ammo for the M-14 he carries, its Perry’s M-14, Perry was wounded at the bend in the river. Welsh starts to unlink the rounds from the guns belt, bullets are eating up the dirt and air around us as the chopper gets closer, I can sense it, I can feel it, I can hear them, hear the bullets striking the LZ, the chopper, the metal, I open up two-three rounds, then the gun misfires, the chopper getting hit, I cannot see it, I can sense it, feel it. The enemy’s in-coming is becoming in tense and heavy. No ones firing back, all the M16 have misfired, Welsh takes my .45 and opens up. The chopper lands, but only for a few seconds and takes off. <br><br>
Did anyone make it on board, I’m wondering, is the gunship gunner all right. I didn’t hear him firing, was he not firing, holding off because of the Marines directly in front of him, is he dead, is it because he doesn’t know where the friendlies are, meanwhile his ship is getting hit, I can hear the impact, the sound that AK47 bullets make as they slice into tin-metal, has the gunner been hit. Damn the gun, Damn the corps, damn the gooks, damn this war. <br><br>
I turn on my back, the chopper is gone. The gun is worthless, the gas pistons blown. Welsh gives his M-14 to his team leader. Then lays on his back next to me and offers me a cigarette. We just lay there mud Marines, on our backs smoking cigarettes. Random shots are fired our way. Welsh shows me he still has three grenades. I have finished re-loading my pistol and hand the machine gun over to Aggie and we take off after the sniper.<br>

